\exercise{3.15}

Does every algorithm have a $\Theta$ running-time equation? In other words, are the upper and lower bounds for the running time (on any specified class of inputs) always the same?

\textbf{Yes}, for any \textit{specific} class of inputs (e.g., worst-case only, or best-case only), every algorithm does have a $\Theta$ running-time equation. This is because, for a fixed class, the running time $T(n)$ is a single well-defined function of $n$, and every such function is $\Theta$ of itself.

\textbf{However}, if we interpret the question as asking whether the upper and lower bounds across \textit{different} classes of inputs are always the same, then the answer is \textbf{no}. For example, sequential search has a worst-case cost of $\Theta(n)$ and a best-case cost of $\Theta(1)$. The bounds differ across input classes, so there is no single $\Theta$ expression that describes the algorithm's running time for \textit{all} inputs of size $n$.

\bigskip

