\exercise{3.16}

Does every problem for which there exists some algorithm have a $\Theta$ running-time equation? In other words, for every problem, and for any specified class of inputs, is there some algorithm whose upper bound is equal to the problem’s lower bound?

\textbf{No.} There are two primary reasons why a problem might not have a tight $\Theta$ running-time equation:
\begin{enumerate}
    \item \textbf{Unknown Optimal Algorithms:} For many complex problems (such as matrix multiplication), there is a gap between the theoretically proven lower bound (e.g., $\Omega(n^2)$) and the best-known algorithm's upper bound. We simply don't yet know if an algorithm exists that perfectly matches the minimum necessary bound for the problem.
    \item \textbf{Blum's Speedup Theorem:} In theoretical computer science, Blum's Speedup Theorem mathematically proves the existence of computable problems that \textit{do not possess any optimal algorithm}. For any possible algorithm that solves such a problem, there exists another algorithm that is significantly faster. Therefore, there is no "best" algorithm whose upper bound matches the problem's fundamental lower bound.
\end{enumerate}

