\exercise{3.17}

Given an array storing integers ordered by value, modify the binary search routine to return the position of the first integer with value $K$ in the situation where $K$ can appear multiple times. Be sure that your algorithm is $\Theta(\log n)$.

\textbf{Answer:} To maintain the strict $\Theta(\log n)$ bound, we cannot drop into a sequential $O(n)$ footprint upon finding $K$. Instead, we must continue the binary search in the left half of the array whenever we encounter $K$ to look for earlier occurrences.

\begin{lstlisting}
int first_occurrence_binary_search(int A[], int n, int K) {
    int low = 0, high = n - 1;
    int first_pos = -1; // Initialize to -1 (not found)
    
    while (low <= high) {
        int mid = low + (high - low) / 2;
        if (A[mid] == K) {
            first_pos = mid;    // Record position of K
            high = mid - 1;     // Important: Search left for earlier occurrences
        } 
        else if (A[mid] < K) {
            low = mid + 1;
        } 
        else {
            high = mid - 1;
        }
    }
    return first_pos;
}
\end{lstlisting}

Because the \texttt{while} loop strictly continues to halve the search space at every step regardless of whether $K$ is found, the routine completes in precisely $\Theta(\log n)$ comparisons.

