\exercise{3.18}

Given an array storing integers ordered by value, modify the binary search routine to return the position of the integer with the greatest value less than $K$ when $K$ itself does not appear in the array. Return \texttt{ERROR} if the least value in the array is greater than $K$.

\textbf{Answer:} When a standard binary search finishes without finding the element, the \texttt{low} and \texttt{high} pointers cross. In this failed crossing state, the \texttt{high} point index naturally rests at exactly the position of the greatest element less than $K$.

\begin{lstlisting}
int greatest_less_than(int A[], int n, int K) {
    int low = 0, high = n - 1;
    
    while (low <= high) {
        int mid = low + (high - low) / 2;
        if (A[mid] < K) {
            low = mid + 1;
        } else {
            high = mid - 1;
        }
    }
    
    // 'high' is now the index of the largest element < K.
    if (high < 0)
        return ERROR; // K is smaller than all elements
    return high;
}
\end{lstlisting}

\textit{Note:} Since the problem states $K$ does not appear in the array, we only need two branches. When the loop terminates, \texttt{high} naturally points to the greatest value less than $K$.

