\exercise{3.19}

Modify the binary search routine to support search in an array of infinite size. Provide an algorithm that can determine the position $n$ boundary in $O(\log n)$ comparisons.

\textbf{Answer:} To search an infinite array, we first need to explicitly and dynamically discover an upper bound for the index. We can do this efficiently using \textbf{Exponential Search} (also known as scaling search operations).

\textbf{Algorithm Steps:}
\begin{enumerate}
    \item We start at index $i = 1$.
    \item We repeatedly double the bounded index ($i = i \times 2$) checking the array limit condition until $A[i] \ge K$.
    \item Once an upper bound $i$ (which equals $2^k$) is found, we know the object $K$ must lay strictly between indices $2^{k-1}$ and $2^k$.
    \item We perform a standard restricted binary search to the finite subarray $A[2^{k-1} \dots 2^k]$.
\end{enumerate}

\textbf{Time Bound Analysis:}
If the smallest value $\ge K$ rests at position $n$, then stepping dynamically in powers of $2$ requires $k \approx \log_2 n$ steps to successfully overshoot $n$. Scanning iteratively for an upper bound therefore takes exactly $O(\log n)$ steps.

Upon finding our limited subarray boundary, applying standard binary search to the interval of size proportional to $2^k - 2^{k-1} = 2^{k-1} \approx \frac{n}{2}$ takes exactly $\log_2(n/2) = \log_2 n - 1 = O(\log n)$ time structure. 

The combined sequential time of dynamic binding and searching is $O(\log n) + O(\log n) = \boxed{O(\log n)}$.

