\exercise{3.21}

\textbf{Algorithm Design:}
Since the \texttt{compare} function only tells us if two pieces are adjacent (an exact match), there is no transitive mathematical property (like greater-than/less-than) that would allow us to sort the pieces organically in $O(N \log N)$ time. We must use targeted iterative searches. Let $N = n \times m$ be the total pieces.

\begin{enumerate}
    \item Start by picking an arbitrary piece (or explicitly finding a corner piece) and place it at the first $(0,0)$ position in our grid.
    \item For every subsequent position in the $n \times m$ grid, look at the physically required adjacent pieces that have already been placed (e.g., the piece immediately to the left, or the piece above).
    \item Iterate through the pool of remaining unplaced pieces, testing them against the placed adjacent piece using the $O(1)$ \texttt{compare} function.
    \item When the match is found, permanently place the piece into the matrix and explicitly remove it from the pool of unplaced candidates.
\end{enumerate}

\textbf{Summation and Closed-Form:}
For the first piece, we expend 0 compares. For the second piece, we may search up to $N-1$ pieces. For the third, $N-2$ pieces, and so on. To place the $k$-th piece, we must search through the remaining $N - k + 1$ pieces. 
In the absolute worst case, the total number of comparisons is the sum of the remaining pieces:
\[
    \sum_{k=1}^{N-1} (N - k) \;=\; \sum_{i=1}^{N-1} i
\]
Using the fundamental arithmetic series formula, the closed-form solution is:
\[
    \boxed{\frac{N(N-1)}{2} \implies \Theta(N^2)}
\]

