\exercise{3.22}

Can the average-case cost be worse than the worst-case cost? Can it be better than the best-case cost?

\textbf{No to both.} The average-case cost is mathematically defined strictly as the expected value (a weighted average) of the running times across all possible inputs of size $n$. 

If $C_i$ is the cost of input $i$, the worst-case cost is definitively $\max(C_i)$ and the best-case cost is $\min(C_i)$. A weighted average of a set of numbers strictly cannot be greater than the maximum number in that set, nor can it ever be less than the minimum number. Therefore, the average-case complexity is permanently and irrevocably bounded between the absolute best and worst-case complexities.

