\exercise{3.23}

Prove that if an algorithm is $\Theta(f(n))$ in the average case, then it is $\Omega(f(n))$ in the worst case.

\begin{proof}
Let $A(n)$ be the average-case running time and $W(n)$ be the worst-case running time. 
By fundamental definition, the worst-case running time must be greater than or equal to the average-case running time for all $n$:
\[
    W(n) \ge A(n)
\]
We are given that $A(n) \in \Theta(f(n))$. The formal definition of $\Theta$ implies that $A(n) \in \Omega(f(n))$, meaning there exists a strictly positive constant $c$ and an integer $n_0$ such that for all $n \ge n_0$:
\[
    A(n) \ge c\,f(n)
\]
Because $W(n) \ge A(n)$, we can combine the sequential inequalities to state that for all $n \ge n_0$:
\[
    W(n) \ge c\,f(n)
\]
This satisfies the formal definition of $\Omega$. Thus, $\boxed{W(n) \in \Omega(f(n))}$.
\end{proof}

