\exercise{3.24}

Prove that if an algorithm is $\Theta(f(n))$ in the average case, then it is $O(f(n))$ in the best case.

\begin{proof}
Let $A(n)$ be the average-case running time and $B(n)$ be the best-case running time. 
By fundamental definition, the best-case running time must be less than or equal to the average-case running time for all $n$:
\[
    B(n) \le A(n)
\]
We are given that $A(n) \in \Theta(f(n))$. The formal definition of $\Theta$ guarantees that $A(n) \in O(f(n))$, meaning there exists a strictly positive constant $c$ and an integer $n_0$ such that for all $n \ge n_0$:
\[
    A(n) \le c\,f(n)
\]
Because $B(n) \le A(n)$, we can chain the inequalities to state that for all $n \ge n_0$:
\[
    B(n) \le A(n) \le c\,f(n) \implies B(n) \le c\,f(n)
\]
This satisfies the formal definition of Big-Oh. Thus, $\boxed{B(n) \in O(f(n))}$.
\end{proof}

